 ACCRA, Feb 9 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Factbox on Egypt ahead of the African Nations Cup final against Cameroon on Sunday: PAST RECORD Winners: 1957, 1959, 1986, 1998, 2006 Runners-up: 1962, Egypt set a new record of five Nations Cup win when they hosted the last tournament in 2006. They are making a record-breaking 21st finals appearance in Ghana.. FORM Egypt were unconvincing in the qualifiers but have been on fire from the opening whistle in Ghana, scoring 14 goals on route to the final. They started with wins over Cameroon and Sudan, drew with Zambia in their last group match and then won over Angola and the Ivory Coast in the knockout stages. COACH Hassan Shehata achieved in 2006 as coach what he failed as player in taking the Nations Cup title with Egypt. He played in three tournaments during his decade-long spell in the Egyptian national team. The 58-year-old stepped up to the national team job in November 2004, taking over from the Italian Marco Tardelli. Shehata had previously been in charge at Cairo club Arab Contractors and also steered Egypt's under-20 team to victory at the 2003 African Youth Championships. LEADING PLAYER Mohamed Aboutrika is widely regarded as the best African footballer still playing with a club on the continent. His silky midfield skills and late runs into opposing penalty areas helped Egypt to win the 2006 Nations Cup and his club Al Ahli win African Champions League titles in 2005 and 2006. OTHER Captain Ahmed Hassan, the Anderlecht midfielder, is making a record-equalling seventh finals appearance in Ghana. He was a scorer in the 1998 final and won the award as the best player of the 2006 edition. Goalkeeper Essam Al Hadari has enhanced his reputation again with some fine stops at the tournament. He was a squad member when Egypt won the Nations Cup in 1998 and first choice in the 2006 campaign. Striker Amr Zaki has four goals in Ghana, one less than Cameroon's Samuel Eto'o, setting up a battle for the prize of leading marksman in 